# Rohitpedia — .cursorrules
# Claude Cursor Agent instructions for this codebase

## ROLE
You are a senior backend engineer working on Rohitpedia — a personal intelligence knowledge system. You write clean, secure, async Python and TypeScript. You know PostgreSQL, pgvector, FastAPI, Next.js, and LLM orchestration patterns.

## BEFORE TOUCHING ANY CODE
1. Read docs/PROTOCOL.md — it defines your workflow and standards
2. Read docs/SRS.md — requirements you must satisfy
3. Read the relevant SUBJECT GUIDE in docs/guides/ for the domain you're working in

## ABSOLUTE RULES (never violate these)

### Data isolation
- EVERY database query must execute within an RLS session
- Set `app.current_tenant` before the first DB query in EVERY function that touches DB
- Never filter by user_id in WHERE clause as a substitute for RLS — do BOTH
- Test isolation after every schema change using the RLS test script in docs/ROADMAP.md

### Idempotency
- Every worker function must be safe to run twice on the same input
- Use `ON CONFLICT DO UPDATE` or `ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING` for ALL upserts
- Check "already processed" state at the start of every job

### LLM usage
- Never feed more than 15k tokens to a single LLM call
- Use vector search (top-8) to select which articles to include — never "all articles"
- Always validate LLM output against a schema before using it
- Log every LLM call to llm_usage table (tokens_in, tokens_out, duration_ms, task_type)
- Default to deterministic code; use LLM only when reasoning or synthesis is genuinely needed

### Raw entries
- Never delete or modify a raw_entry after creation
- raw_entries are append-only truth

## CODE STANDARDS

### Python
- Async everywhere: `async def`, `await`, `AsyncSession`
- Type hints on every function parameter and return value
- Pydantic for all data validation (never raw dict manipulation)
- structlog for structured logging (never f-string logs with user content)
- Never catch bare `Exception` silently — log and re-raise

### SQL
- Parameterised queries only — never string concatenation
- Migrations for every schema change — never ALTER TABLE in production manually
- `ON DELETE CASCADE` on all foreign keys to user_id
- Explicit B-Tree indexes on (user_id), (user_id, slug), (user_id, context)

### Error handling
- LLM calls: retry 3× with exponential backoff, then mark job failed
- Worker failures: log with job_id and entry_id (not user content), mark job failed, don't crash worker
- Validation failures: raise specific exception type, log, don't swallow

### Security
- Validate all slugs: `^[a-zA-Z0-9._/-]+$` pattern
- Validate media paths: no `..`, must be within MEDIA_DIR
- Validate Telegram webhook secret on every request
- Never log PII: no entry.body, no user email, no telegram_id in plain text
- All secrets from env vars via pydantic Settings class

## CHUNKING RULES (PDF and article ingestion)

### Wiki articles (for embedding)
1. Split on `##` and `###` markdown headers
2. Sections > 512 tokens: recursive split with 100-token overlap
3. Minimum chunk size: 80 characters (skip stubs)
4. Each chunk stores: article_id, chunk_index, section_header, chunk_text, embedding

### PDFs
- ≤ 20 pages: extract full structured markdown via Docling, store in raw_entries.body, absorb as one call
- > 20 pages: split by chapter headings or 20-page windows, absorb each section independently, meta-absorb creates hub article
- ALWAYS store full raw extracted text in raw_entries.body regardless of length
- NEVER throw away raw content

## URL EXTRACTION ORDER
Always try in this order, move to next if < 200 chars returned:
1. Firecrawl API (if FIRECRAWL_API_KEY set)
2. Jina Reader: `https://r.jina.ai/{url}` (free, no key)
3. trafilatura
4. Playwright headless (slow, last resort)
5. Fallback: og:title + url stored, no body

## WIKILINK EXTRACTION
ALWAYS use markdown-it-py AST parser. NEVER use regex for wikilink extraction.
```python
from markdown_it import MarkdownIt
# See docs/guides/SUBJECT_GUIDE_Python_FastAPI.md for full implementation
```

## DATABASE TRANSACTION PATTERN
Article writes MUST be atomic:
```python
async with db.begin():
    await set_rls(db, user_id)
    await upsert_article(...)
    await write_backlinks(...)
    await write_facets(...)
    await mark_entry_absorbed(...)
```

## LLM PROVIDER PATTERN
Always use the provider abstraction:
```python
provider = get_provider("absorb")  # returns correct model for task
result = await provider.complete(prompt, max_tokens=1000)
```
Never call Gemini/Ollama APIs directly — always go through the provider.

## INTELLIGENCE ENGINE RULES
- PPR runs on NetworkX graph built from backlinks table
- RNS scoring: R × N × (0.5 + 0.5×S) × decay_w
- N = 0 for already-linked pairs (check BOTH directions)
- Filter dislike_pairs BEFORE scoring, not after
- Top-8 non-noise candidates → ONE LLM call for rationale (not one call per pair)
- Nothing enters the wiki automatically — all suggestions go to tunnel_suggestions table for human review

## WHAT CURSOR SHOULD AND SHOULD NOT DO

### Should do
- Write complete, working implementations — not stubs or TODOs
- Include error handling in every function
- Include the RLS context-setting call in every DB-touching function
- Follow the exact chunking and extraction strategies from this file
- Suggest the cheapest appropriate model for each LLM task
- Write tests alongside implementations

### Should not do
- Write raw SQL with string concatenation
- Omit the RLS session variable setup
- Call the LLM for tasks that can be done deterministically
- Create global mutable state (no module-level DB connections)
- Add dependencies that duplicate what Postgres/stdlib already provides
- Skip error handling ("I'll add this later")
- Write synchronous DB calls in async functions

## PHASE AWARENESS
Current phase: Phase 1 (Foundation + Capture Loop)

Phase 1 is complete when:
- [ ] RLS isolation test passes
- [ ] All media types captured and extracted
- [ ] Text → wiki article pipeline in < 90s
- [ ] Bot queries answered in < 2s
- [ ] Two users fully isolated

Do NOT implement Phase 2 (intelligence) features until Phase 1 gate passes.

